# nullprobe Architecture

## src/ Structure

```
src/
├── index.ts                    # CLI entry (commander) — add new commands here
├── types.ts                    # Shared types (AIPlatform, InitAnswers, etc.)
├── commands/                   # Thin handlers — delegate to flows + scaffolder
├── flows/                      # All user interaction (inquirer prompts)
│   ├── init-flow.ts            # Conversational init dialogue
│   └── update-flow.ts          # Conversational update check
├── scaffolder/
│   ├── index.ts                # Orchestrates writes — THE WIRING FILE (see below)
│   ├── file-writer.ts          # mkdir + writeFile utility
│   └── templates/              # Embedded string constants (one file per output file)
│       ├── ai-framework.ts     # Reads AI_FRAMEWORK.md from repo root at runtime
│       ├── skill-*.ts          # Each skill = one template file
│       ├── wiki-index.ts       # wiki/index.md template
│       └── wiki-log.ts         # wiki/log.md template (function, takes today's date)
└── github/
    ├── sources.ts              # Source repo definitions (single source of truth)
    └── client.ts               # Fetch latest commit per repo
```

## Critical Wiring Rule

When adding a new skill or output file:
1. Create `src/scaffolder/templates/skill-<name>.ts` exporting a string constant
2. Import it in `src/scaffolder/index.ts`
3. Add it to the `files` array in the `scaffold()` function
4. Also create `.claude/skills/<name>/SKILL.md` for this project's own use

Missing step 3 means the skill template exists but is never written to disk.

## Key Patterns

- **Templates are embedded strings** — no runtime file reads (except `ai-framework.ts` which reads from repo root)
- **Flow layer = user interaction** — all prompts live in `flows/`, scaffolder writes unconditionally
- **Overwrite guard** is in `init-flow.ts`, not in the scaffolder
- **GitHub calls are serial** — `checkAllSources()` loops, never concurrent

## Adding a New Command

1. Add command handler in `src/commands/<name>.ts`
2. Add conversational flow in `src/flows/<name>-flow.ts`
3. Register in `src/index.ts` via `program.command(...)`
